1) Explain what is Pod 

A pod is smallest unit of deployment 
A pod can contain one or more containers 
Mostly we see applications deployed on pod with a single container 
Pod shares network space and storage space 
That is, containers inside same pod can communicate with each other using localhost becase they are sharing 
the network space, pod gets and private IP .This IP is reachable within cluster from any node.

2) What are the different method we can deploy the applications?
We can deploy applicaitons using imperative approach or declarative approach.
In declarative approach, we pull all the details in YAML decument.and we pass it on to kubernetes cluster, cluster 
takes care of creating the resources accordingly. In imperative approach, we put everything in the command itself.

3) How will you deply application in imperative approach?
# kubectl run nginx --image='nginx:latest' --port=80 
# kubectl get pods -> To check the status
# kubectl get pods -o wide -> To see more details about the pod 
Note: if we want to access this pod from my local laptop, which is not inside kubernetes cluster, it is 
not possible. if we want to access this pod from outside we need to expose application to the 
out side world, to expose out side we can use service or ingress controllers.

Temporarily we can expose this appllication via port mapping 
# kubectl port-forward pod/nginx 8080:80
localhost port 8080
nginx is listening on 80 
After running this command we can put localhost:8080 --> The traffic is routed to nginx which is running
inside kubernetes cluster. This is only for testing purpose, This is not the way to expose applicaitons 
to the outside world in real world situations.
































